ref: Conf: Conf.on Nucl.Data For Sci.and Technol.,Mito 1988, p.275 (1988)
title: -Differential Cross Sections for Gamma-Ray Production By 14 Mev Neutrons With Several Elements In Structural Materials.

x4codes.shortRef: Conf: Conf.on Nucl.Data For Sci.and Technol.,Mito 1988, p.275 (1988)

x4freetext: -DIFFERENTIAL CROSS SECTIONS FOR GAMMA-RAY PRODUCTION
BY 14 MEV NEUTRONS WITH SEVERAL ELEMENTS IN STRUCTURAL
MATERIALS.
OKTAVIAN PULSED 14 MEV NEUTRON SOURCE FACILITY OF
OSAKA UNIVERSITY. THE PULSE WIDTH WAS 3 NSEC AND THE
REPETITION RATE WAS 2 MHZ.
1.0E+03 NEUTRONS/PULSE WERE PRODUCED BY BOMBAR-
DING A 10 CI TITANIUM-TRITIUM TARGET WITH DEUTERONS OF
243 KEV.
TIME-OF-FLIGHT TECHNIQUES WERE USED TO REDUCE THE
BACKGROUND OF SCATTERED NEUTRONS FROM THE SAMPLE,
ROOM-RETURNED NEUTRONS AND GAMMA-RAYS.
A 180 CM3 GERMANIUM DETECTOR WAS USED TO MEA-
SURE DISCRETE GAMMA-RAYS BETWEEN 500 AND 3000 KEV. THE
DETECTOR WAS PLACED IN A SHIELD OF LEAD, PARAFFIN,
CONCRETE ETC. AT A DISTANCE OF 150 CM FROM THE SAMPLE.
THE DISTANCE FROM THE TARGET TO THE SAMPLES WAS 20 CM.
SEVEN ANGLES FROM 30 TO 150 DEGREES IN THE LAB SYSTEM
BETWEEN THE INCIDENT NEUTRONS AND THE EMITTED GAMMA-
RAYS WERE MEASURED. THE DETECTOR EFFICIENCY WAS DETER-
MINED USING SOURCES OF CS-137, CO-60, NA-22, NA-24,
MN-56 AND NI-57.
A SODIUM-IODODE CRYSTAL OF 12.7 CM DIAMETER AND
12.7 CM IN LENGTH WAS USED TO MEASURE THE ENERGY DIS-
TRIBUTIONS OF GAMMA-RAYS FROM 0.7 TO 10 MEV. THE DE-
TECTOR WAS PLACED IN A HEAVY SHIELDING WITH A FLIGHT
PATH OF 316 CM FROM THE SAMPLE. MEASUREMENTS WERE MADE
AT 45 AND 125 OR 135 DEGREES. UNFOLDING OF THE SPECTRA
WAS PERFORMED USING CALCULATED RESPONSE FUNCTIONS WITH
THE COMPUTER CODE FERDOR.
A NE 213 LIQUID SCINTILLATION DETECTOR, LOCATED
AT A DISTANCE OF 4 M FROM THE NEUTRON SOURCE IN THE
DEUTERON BEAM DIRECTION, OPERATING IN TIME-OF-FLIGHT
MODE WITH NEUTRON-GAMMA DISCRIMINATION, WAS USED TO
MONITOR THE RELATIVE NEUTRON YIELD. ABSOLUTE CALIBRA-
TION OF THIS DETECTOR WAS MADE BY MEASURING THE IN-
DUCED ACTIVITIES IN IRRADIATED ALUMINUM AND NIOBIUM
FOILS.
.THE SAMPLES WERE THE NATURAL ELEMENTS CARBON, ALUMI-
NUM, SILICON, CHROMIUM, IRON, NICKEL, COPPER AND
MOLYBDENUM.
.FOR THE DISCRETE GAMMA-RAY MEASUREMENTS THE SAMPLES
WERE HOLLOW CYLINDERS OF 30 MM O.D. X 26 MM I.D. X
70 MM LONG. FOR AL, THE WALL THICKNESS WAS 5 MM. THE
SI SAMPLE WAS A 25 MM DIAMETER X 50 MM LONG CYLINDER.
THE C SAMPLE WAS A HOLLOW CYLINDER OF 40 MM O.D. X
15 MM I.D. X 50 MM LONG.
.FOR THE ENERGY DISTRIBUTION MEASUREMENTS THE SAMPLES
WERE PURE ELEMENTAL DISCS OF 10 CM DIAMTER AND 5 MM
THICK, EXCEPT FOR THE SI AND FE SAMPLES.
.DATA WERE CORRECTED FOR THE NEUTRON SPECTRUM, NEUTRON
MULTIPLE SCATTERING AND ATTENUATION IN THE SAMPLE AND
FOR GAMMA-RAY ATTENUATION.

x4code.headerHelp: Error in value of quantity, defined under ERR-ANALYS

x4freetext: THE TOTAL ERRORS WERE COMPOSED OF THE
FOLLOWING CONTRIBUTIONS. STATISTICAL ERRORS FOR INDI-
VIDUAL DISCRETE GAMMA-RAY PEAKS, 1 TO 7 PERCENT. UN-
CERTAINTIES IN THE PEAK EFFICIENCIES OF THE GE DETEC-
TOR, 4.5 PERCENT BELOW 1.3 MEV AND 6.0 PERCENT ABOVE.
THE ERRORS IN THE NEUTRON FLUX DETERMINATION WERE 7
TO 10 PERCENT. IN THE CASE OF THE NAI MEASUREMENTS,
ERRORS ACCORDING TO THE UNFOLDING ARE ALSO INCLUDED.
.ANGLE-INTEGRATED CROSS SECTIONS FOR THE DISCRETE
GAMMA-RAYS WERE OBTAINED BY LEGENDRE POLYNOMIAL
FITTING.
.DATA WERE OBTAINED FROM THE MAIN REF.
N.O.
